if(!window.MM) window.MM={};
window.MM['ent_p2_congenital']=[
  {q:"A 7-year-old child presents with a midline neck swelling that moves upward on tongue protrusion and swallowing. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Branchial cyst","Thyroglossal cyst","Cystic hygroma","Dermoid cyst","Laryngocele"],a:1,e:"Thyroglossal cyst is the commonest congenital neck cyst arising from persistent thyroglossal duct remnants. Midline neck swelling develops clinically and characteristically moves with tongue protrusion.<br><br>The tract remains attached embryologically to foramen cecum through tongue musculature.<br><br>Branchial cyst (option A), cystic hygroma (option C), dermoid cyst (option D), and laryngocele (option E) show different anatomical behavior.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The definitive surgical treatment for thyroglossal cyst is:",o:["Sistrunk operation","Incision and drainage","Simple aspiration","Radical neck dissection","Hemithyroidectomy"],a:0,e:"Sistrunk operation is the standard surgical treatment for thyroglossal cyst. Recurrent infection develops clinically after incomplete excision of the tract.<br><br>The procedure removes cyst, tract, and central portion of hyoid bone to reduce recurrence.<br><br>Simple aspiration (option C), incision and drainage (option B), neck dissection (option D), and hemithyroidectomy (option E) are inadequate procedures.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A painless fluctuant swelling along anterior border of sternocleidomastoid muscle in a young adult is most likely:",o:["Branchial cyst","Dermoid cyst","Thyroglossal cyst","Ranula","Cystic hygroma"],a:0,e:"Branchial cyst classically presents as painless fluctuant swelling along upper anterior border of sternocleidomastoid muscle. Infection develops clinically after repeated upper respiratory tract infections.<br><br>The lesion arises from persistent remnants of second branchial cleft.<br><br>Thyroglossal cyst (option C), dermoid cyst (option B), ranula (option D), and cystic hygroma (option E) occupy different locations.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A newborn presents with soft brilliantly transilluminant swelling in posterior triangle of neck causing respiratory distress. The diagnosis is:",o:["Branchial cyst","Thyroglossal cyst","Dermoid cyst","Cystic hygroma","Sebaceous cyst"],a:3,e:"Cystic hygroma is a congenital lymphatic malformation commonly involving posterior triangle of neck. Airway compromise develops clinically in large lesions of infancy.<br><br>The lesion consists of multiloculated lymph-filled cystic spaces and transilluminates brilliantly.<br><br>Branchial cyst (option A), thyroglossal cyst (option B), dermoid cyst (option C), and sebaceous cyst (option E) transilluminate poorly or not at all.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A thyroglossal cyst moves upward during tongue protrusion because of attachment to the:",o:["Hyoid bone and tongue base","Cricoid cartilage","Thyroid cartilage","Sternocleidomastoid muscle","Trachea only"],a:0,e:"Thyroglossal duct remnants maintain attachment to tongue base through hyoid-related embryological tract. Midline neck movement develops clinically during swallowing and tongue protrusion.<br><br>This anatomical relation forms the basis of Sistrunk operation.<br><br>Thyroid cartilage (option C), cricoid cartilage (option B), sternocleidomastoid muscle (option D), and trachea alone (option E) are less relevant attachments.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with infected thyroglossal cyst initially requires:",o:["Immediate Sistrunk operation","Radiotherapy","Antibiotics and infection control","Radical neck dissection","Chemotherapy"],a:2,e:"Infected thyroglossal cyst should first be treated conservatively with antibiotics. Pain and erythema develop clinically during acute infection.<br><br>Definitive surgery is delayed until inflammation subsides to reduce operative complications and recurrence.<br><br>Immediate surgery (option A), radiotherapy (option B), neck dissection (option D), and chemotherapy (option E) are inappropriate initial approaches.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common branchial anomaly arises from the:",o:["Second branchial cleft","First branchial cleft","Third branchial cleft","Fourth branchial cleft","Fifth branchial pouch"],a:0,e:"Second branchial cleft anomalies are the commonest congenital branchial lesions. Lateral neck swelling develops clinically in older children and young adults.<br><br>Failure of obliteration of cervical sinus contributes to cyst formation embryologically.<br><br>First cleft (option B), third cleft (option C), fourth cleft (option D), and fifth pouch anomalies (option E) are uncommon.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A branchial fistula usually opens externally along the:",o:["Lower anterior border of sternocleidomastoid","Posterior triangle apex","Midline neck","Suprasternal notch","Submental region"],a:0,e:"Branchial fistula commonly opens externally near lower anterior border of sternocleidomastoid muscle. Persistent mucoid discharge develops clinically from the opening.<br><br>The tract may extend internally toward tonsillar fossa embryologically.<br><br>Midline neck (option C), posterior triangle apex (option B), suprasternal notch (option D), and submental region (option E) are incorrect sites.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A cystic hygroma primarily arises from congenital malformation of:",o:["Lymphatic system","Salivary ducts","Thyroid follicles","Branchial arches only","Parathyroid tissue"],a:0,e:"Cystic hygroma results from congenital sequestration of lymphatic tissue failing to communicate normally. Massive neck swelling develops clinically in infancy.<br><br>The lesion frequently infiltrates tissue planes and may extend into mediastinum.<br><br>Thyroid follicles (option C), salivary ducts (option B), branchial arches alone (option D), and parathyroid tissue (option E) are unrelated origins.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A child undergoes Sistrunk operation. Removal of which structure is essential to reduce recurrence?",o:["Thyroid cartilage","Cricoid cartilage","Central hyoid bone","Entire thyroid gland","Submandibular gland"],a:2,e:"Removal of central hyoid bone is crucial because thyroglossal tract commonly traverses this structure. Recurrence develops clinically after incomplete tract excision.<br><br>Sistrunk procedure significantly lowers recurrence compared with simple cyst excision alone.<br><br>Thyroid cartilage (option A), cricoid cartilage (option B), entire thyroid gland (option D), and submandibular gland (option E) are unnecessary removals.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A 20-year-old patient presents with painless lateral neck cystic swelling after upper respiratory tract infection. FNAC reveals cholesterol crystals. The diagnosis is:",o:["Thyroglossal cyst","Dermoid cyst","Branchial cyst","Laryngocele","Lipoma"],a:2,e:"Branchial cyst aspirate classically contains cholesterol crystals and keratinous debris. Painless lateral neck swelling develops clinically after secondary infection episodes.<br><br>The lesion usually lies deep to sternocleidomastoid in upper neck.<br><br>Thyroglossal cyst (option A), dermoid cyst (option B), laryngocele (option D), and lipoma (option E) show different cytological findings.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The investigation most useful before thyroglossal cyst surgery is:",o:["Thyroid scan or ultrasound","Pure tone audiometry","Bronchoscopy","Sialography","Tympanometry"],a:0,e:"Preoperative imaging confirms presence of normally located thyroid tissue before thyroglossal surgery. Hypothyroidism develops clinically if ectopic thyroid tissue is removed accidentally.<br><br>Ultrasound effectively evaluates thyroid anatomy and associated lesions.<br><br>Audiometry (option B), bronchoscopy (option C), sialography (option D), and tympanometry (option E) are unrelated investigations.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A congenital neck lesion that classically transilluminates is:",o:["Branchial cyst","Thyroglossal cyst","Dermoid cyst","Cystic hygroma","Sebaceous cyst"],a:3,e:"Cystic hygroma contains lymphatic fluid-filled spaces producing brilliant transillumination. Respiratory distress develops clinically in large cervical lesions.<br><br>The lesion commonly occupies posterior triangle and infiltrates surrounding fascial planes extensively.<br><br>Branchial cyst (option A), thyroglossal cyst (option B), dermoid cyst (option C), and sebaceous cyst (option E) transilluminate poorly.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A child develops recurrence after simple excision of thyroglossal cyst. The most likely reason is:",o:["Malignant transformation","Incomplete tract removal","Radiation fibrosis","Salivary obstruction","Neural injury"],a:1,e:"Recurrence commonly follows incomplete excision of thyroglossal duct remnants. Recurrent midline neck swelling develops clinically months or years later.<br><br>Residual epithelial tract near hyoid bone continues secreting cystic contents.<br><br>Malignant transformation (option A), radiation fibrosis (option C), salivary obstruction (option D), and neural injury (option E) are less common causes.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A congenital fistula opening near anterior sternocleidomastoid and extending internally toward tonsillar fossa is derived from:",o:["First branchial cleft","Second branchial cleft","Third branchial pouch","Thyroglossal tract","Lymphatic sac"],a:1,e:"Second branchial fistula typically tracks from neck skin toward tonsillar fossa internally. Mucoid discharge develops clinically from external opening.<br><br>The tract courses between internal and external carotid arteries embryologically.<br><br>First cleft (option A), third pouch (option C), thyroglossal tract (option D), and lymphatic sac (option E) follow different pathways.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A newborn with giant cystic hygroma develops airway obstruction immediately after birth. The preferred emergency management is:",o:["Observation only","Emergency airway stabilization","Chemotherapy","Thyroidectomy","Radiation therapy"],a:1,e:"Large cervical cystic hygromas may compress airway critically in neonates. Respiratory distress develops clinically immediately after delivery in severe lesions.<br><br>Airway stabilization takes priority before definitive surgical or sclerotherapy management.<br><br>Observation (option A), chemotherapy (option C), thyroidectomy (option D), and radiotherapy (option E) are inappropriate emergencies.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common location of thyroglossal cyst is:",o:["Midline below hyoid bone","Posterior triangle","Parotid region","Supraclavicular fossa","Retropharyngeal space"],a:0,e:"Thyroglossal cyst commonly presents in midline close to hyoid bone level. Swelling movement develops clinically during deglutition and tongue protrusion.<br><br>Persistence of embryological thyroglossal tract explains this characteristic location.<br><br>Posterior triangle (option B), parotid region (option C), supraclavicular fossa (option D), and retropharyngeal space (option E) are uncommon sites.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A lateral congenital neck cyst appearing after adolescence should raise suspicion of:",o:["Metastatic cystic squamous carcinoma","Dermoid cyst only","Sebaceous cyst only","Thyroid adenoma","Lipoma"],a:0,e:"Cystic lateral neck masses in adults may represent metastatic squamous carcinoma until proven otherwise. Dysphagia and occult primary lesions develop clinically in some patients.<br><br>Careful head and neck evaluation becomes essential before labeling lesion as benign branchial cyst.<br><br>Dermoid cyst (option B), sebaceous cyst (option C), thyroid adenoma (option D), and lipoma (option E) are less concerning possibilities.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A congenital lesion of neck associated with Turner syndrome is:",o:["Thyroglossal cyst","Branchial cyst","Dermoid cyst","Cystic hygroma","Ranula"],a:3,e:"Cystic hygroma demonstrates association with chromosomal disorders including Turner syndrome. Large posterior cervical swelling develops clinically during infancy or prenatal scans.<br><br>Abnormal lymphatic development contributes to lesion formation embryologically.<br><br>Thyroglossal cyst (option A), branchial cyst (option B), dermoid cyst (option C), and ranula (option E) lack strong associations.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with branchial cyst undergoes definitive treatment. The preferred management is:",o:["Repeated aspiration","Oral steroids only","Complete surgical excision","Radiotherapy","Observation lifelong"],a:2,e:"Complete surgical excision is definitive treatment for branchial cysts and fistulas. Recurrent infection develops clinically if lesions remain untreated.<br><br>Careful dissection prevents recurrence and injury to adjacent neurovascular structures.<br><br>Repeated aspiration (option A), steroids (option B), radiotherapy (option D), and lifelong observation (option E) are inadequate strategies.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A 24-year-old patient presents with a painless cystic swelling at the upper anterior border of sternocleidomastoid muscle. Which embryological structure most commonly gives rise to this lesion?",o:["First pharyngeal pouch","Second branchial cleft","Third branchial pouch","Thyroglossal duct","Tuberculum impar"],a:1,e:"Second branchial cleft anomalies are the commonest congenital lateral neck lesions encountered clinically. Painless fluctuant swelling develops clinically in late childhood or early adulthood.<br><br>Failure of obliteration of the cervical sinus during embryogenesis leads to branchial cyst formation.<br><br>First pouch (option A), third pouch (option C), thyroglossal duct (option D), and tuberculum impar (option E) produce different anomalies.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A thyroglossal cyst located at base of tongue may clinically present with:",o:["Conductive hearing loss","Inspiratory stridor and dysphagia","Facial nerve palsy","Trismus only","Hemoptysis"],a:1,e:"Lingual thyroglossal cysts near foramen cecum may obstruct upper airway and swallowing pathways. Dysphagia and stridor develop clinically in larger lesions.<br><br>These lesions arise from persistent superior thyroglossal duct remnants near tongue base.<br><br>Conductive hearing loss (option A), facial palsy (option C), isolated trismus (option D), and hemoptysis (option E) are less characteristic manifestations.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"During excision of a second branchial fistula, the tract typically passes between the:",o:["External and internal carotid arteries","Internal jugular vein and vagus nerve","Common carotid artery and trachea","Facial artery and facial vein","Lingual nerve and hypoglossal nerve"],a:0,e:"A second branchial fistula characteristically ascends between internal and external carotid arteries toward tonsillar fossa. Recurrent mucous discharge develops clinically from external opening.<br><br>Knowledge of this anatomical course is crucial during definitive surgical excision.<br><br>Internal jugular-vagus relation (option B), carotid-tracheal plane (option C), facial vessels (option D), and lingual-hypoglossal relation (option E) are incorrect pathways.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A 40-year-old smoker presents with cystic neck swelling clinically resembling branchial cyst. Which diagnosis must be excluded first?",o:["Thyroglossal cyst","Cystic hygroma","Metastatic squamous cell carcinoma","Dermoid cyst","Lipoma"],a:2,e:"Cystic metastatic squamous carcinoma from occult oropharyngeal primary may mimic branchial cyst in adults. Dysphagia and cervical lymphadenopathy develop clinically in advanced disease.<br><br>Adult lateral neck cysts should therefore be considered malignant until proven otherwise.<br><br>Thyroglossal cyst (option A), cystic hygroma (option B), dermoid cyst (option D), and lipoma (option E) are less dangerous possibilities.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A neonate with massive cystic hygroma extending into mediastinum is planned for definitive treatment. The preferred modern non-surgical therapy for unresectable lesions is:",o:["Intralesional sclerotherapy","Radioiodine ablation","Radical neck dissection","Chemotherapy","Thyroid suppression therapy"],a:0,e:"Large infiltrative cystic hygromas may be difficult to excise completely because of extension into vital structures. Airway compromise develops clinically in extensive lesions.<br><br>Intralesional sclerotherapy using agents such as bleomycin or OK-432 provides effective minimally invasive management.<br><br>Radioiodine ablation (option B), neck dissection (option C), chemotherapy (option D), and thyroid suppression (option E) are inappropriate treatments.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A 10-year-old child presents with a painless midline neck swelling that moves upward on tongue protrusion. The embryological origin of this lesion is failure of obliteration of:",o:["Thyroglossal duct","Branchial pouch","Cervical sinus","Lymphatic sac","Tuberculum impar"],a:0,e:"Thyroglossal cyst results from persistence of embryonic thyroglossal duct remnants. Midline neck swelling develops clinically and typically moves with swallowing and tongue protrusion.<br><br>The thyroid gland normally descends from foramen cecum to lower neck during development.<br><br>Branchial pouch (option B), cervical sinus (option C), lymphatic sac (option D), and tuberculum impar (option E) produce different congenital anomalies.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A thyroglossal cyst is most commonly located:",o:["In posterior triangle","Near angle of mandible","Lateral to sternocleidomastoid","Midline below hyoid bone","In parotid region"],a:3,e:"Most thyroglossal cysts occur close to hyoid bone in the midline neck. Swelling movement develops clinically during deglutition and tongue protrusion.<br><br>Persistence of duct remnants near hyoid explains this characteristic anatomical location.<br><br>Posterior triangle (option A), angle of mandible (option B), lateral sternocleidomastoid region (option C), and parotid region (option E) are uncommon sites.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The investigation most important before excision of thyroglossal cyst is:",o:["Pure tone audiometry","Thyroid ultrasound","Bronchoscopy","Sialography","Barium swallow"],a:1,e:"Preoperative ultrasound confirms the presence of normally located thyroid tissue before surgery. Hypothyroidism develops clinically if ectopic thyroid tissue is removed accidentally.<br><br>Ultrasound also helps identify associated thyroid abnormalities and cyst characteristics.<br><br>Audiometry (option A), bronchoscopy (option C), sialography (option D), and barium swallow (option E) are unrelated investigations.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The standard surgical treatment for thyroglossal cyst is:",o:["Sistrunk operation","Aspiration only","Incision and drainage","Radical neck dissection","Hemithyroidectomy"],a:0,e:"Sistrunk operation is the definitive treatment for thyroglossal cysts and fistulas. Recurrence develops clinically after incomplete excision procedures.<br><br>The operation includes removal of cyst, tract, and central hyoid bone segment.<br><br>Incision and drainage (option C), aspiration (option B), neck dissection (option D), and hemithyroidectomy (option E) are inappropriate definitive procedures.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A child presents with infected thyroglossal cyst. The initial management should be:",o:["Immediate Sistrunk operation","Radical neck dissection","Radioiodine therapy","Broad-spectrum antibiotics","Total thyroidectomy"],a:3,e:"Acute infection should first be controlled before definitive surgery is attempted. Painful erythematous swelling develops clinically during secondary bacterial infection.<br><br>Operating in acutely inflamed tissues increases recurrence and complication risks significantly.<br><br>Immediate surgery (option A), neck dissection (option B), radioiodine therapy (option C), and thyroidectomy (option E) are inappropriate initial measures.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A thyroglossal cyst moves with tongue protrusion because it is attached to the:",o:["Hyoid bone and foramen cecum tract","Thyroid cartilage","Cricoid cartilage","Tracheal rings","Sternocleidomastoid muscle"],a:0,e:"Persistent thyroglossal tract retains embryological connection between hyoid region and tongue base. Characteristic movement develops clinically during tongue protrusion.<br><br>This anatomical relationship forms the basis for removing central hyoid bone during surgery.<br><br>Thyroid cartilage (option B), cricoid cartilage (option C), tracheal rings (option D), and sternocleidomastoid muscle (option E) are unrelated attachments.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"Recurrence after thyroglossal cyst surgery most commonly occurs because of:",o:["Incomplete excision of tract","Radiation fibrosis","Malignant transformation","Salivary fistula formation","Thyroid storm"],a:0,e:"Residual epithelial tract remnants are the commonest cause of recurrence after thyroglossal surgery. Recurrent midline neck swelling develops clinically months or years later.<br><br>Simple cyst excision without hyoid removal carries particularly high recurrence rates.<br><br>Malignant transformation (option C), radiation fibrosis (option B), salivary fistula (option D), and thyroid storm (option E) are less relevant causes.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"During Sistrunk operation, which structure is removed routinely?",o:["Entire thyroid gland","Sternohyoid muscle","Submandibular gland","Central portion of hyoid bone","Cricoid cartilage"],a:3,e:"Central hyoid bone removal is essential because thyroglossal tract usually passes through or above this structure. Persistent discharge develops clinically if remnants remain.<br><br>This step significantly reduces postoperative recurrence rates.<br><br>Entire thyroid gland (option A), sternohyoid muscle (option B), submandibular gland (option C), and cricoid cartilage (option E) are not routinely excised.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 5-year-old child presents with recurrent discharging sinus in midline neck after previous surgery. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Branchial fistula","Dermoid cyst","Persistent thyroglossal fistula","Cystic hygroma","Laryngocele"],a:2,e:"Persistent thyroglossal fistula commonly follows incomplete treatment of infected cysts or inadequate surgery. Mucoid discharge develops clinically through midline neck opening.<br><br>Residual duct epithelium continues secreting cystic material chronically.<br><br>Branchial fistula (option A), dermoid cyst (option B), cystic hygroma (option D), and laryngocele (option E) have different anatomical locations.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A lingual thyroglossal cyst may clinically produce:",o:["Inspiratory stridor","Facial asymmetry","Conductive hearing loss","Trismus only","Bell palsy"],a:0,e:"Lingual thyroglossal cysts near tongue base may obstruct upper airway passages. Dysphagia and stridor develop clinically when lesions enlarge significantly.<br><br>These cysts arise from persistent superior portions of thyroglossal tract.<br><br>Facial asymmetry (option B), hearing loss (option C), isolated trismus (option D), and Bell palsy (option E) are less characteristic features.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A thyroglossal cyst should not be excised before confirming:",o:["Presence of normal salivary glands","Presence of normal cervical lymph nodes","Integrity of facial nerve","Presence of normally located thyroid tissue","Normal vocal cord mobility"],a:3,e:"Some thyroglossal cysts may contain the only functioning thyroid tissue in the body. Severe hypothyroidism develops clinically if ectopic thyroid tissue is removed unknowingly.<br><br>Ultrasound and thyroid scanning help avoid this important complication.<br><br>Salivary glands (option A), lymph nodes (option B), facial nerve integrity (option C), and vocal cord mobility (option E) are less critical considerations.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The epithelial lining of a thyroglossal cyst is most commonly:",o:["Stratified squamous or columnar epithelium","Transitional epithelium only","Keratinized skin epithelium","Respiratory cartilage","Endothelium"],a:0,e:"Thyroglossal cysts may show either stratified squamous or pseudostratified columnar epithelial lining. Recurrent infection develops clinically in longstanding lesions.<br><br>The variable epithelial pattern reflects embryological origin and chronic inflammatory changes.<br><br>Transitional epithelium (option B), keratinized skin epithelium (option C), cartilage (option D), and endothelium (option E) are incorrect linings.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 35-year-old adult presents with newly developed midline neck cystic swelling. The most important differential diagnosis to exclude is:",o:["Lipoma","Sebaceous cyst","Metastatic papillary thyroid carcinoma","Branchial fistula","Laryngocele"],a:2,e:"Adult cystic midline neck masses may occasionally represent metastatic thyroid carcinoma. Cervical nodal disease develops clinically in papillary thyroid malignancy.<br><br>Histopathological examination remains essential after excision of suspicious lesions.<br><br>Lipoma (option A), sebaceous cyst (option B), branchial fistula (option D), and laryngocele (option E) are less concerning differentials.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"Thyroglossal cyst carcinoma most commonly shows which histological type?",o:["Medullary carcinoma","Squamous carcinoma","Follicular carcinoma","Papillary carcinoma","Anaplastic carcinoma"],a:3,e:"Papillary carcinoma is the commonest malignancy arising in thyroglossal cyst remnants. Painless enlarging neck mass develops clinically in affected adults.<br><br>The tumor resembles papillary carcinoma occurring within thyroid gland proper.<br><br>Medullary carcinoma (option A), squamous carcinoma (option B), follicular carcinoma (option C), and anaplastic carcinoma (option E) are less frequent.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops postoperative recurrence after simple thyroglossal cyst excision performed without hyoid removal. The recurrence is mainly because the tract:",o:["Ends within sternocleidomastoid muscle","Passes through central hyoid region","Communicates with parotid gland","Drains into pyriform fossa","Arises from branchial pouch"],a:1,e:"The thyroglossal tract commonly traverses close to or through central hyoid bone. Persistent epithelial remnants develop clinically into recurrent cysts after incomplete surgery.<br><br>Sistrunk operation specifically addresses this anatomical relationship effectively.<br><br>Sternocleidomastoid attachment (option A), parotid communication (option C), pyriform drainage (option D), and branchial origin (option E) are incorrect.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A child presents with recurrent infection of thyroglossal cyst. The most common organism cultured is:",o:["Mycobacterium tuberculosis","Candida albicans","Pseudomonas aeruginosa","Staphylococcus aureus","Klebsiella pneumoniae"],a:3,e:"Secondary bacterial infection of thyroglossal cysts commonly involves skin flora such as Staphylococcus aureus. Painful erythematous swelling develops clinically during infection episodes.<br><br>Repeated infections increase fibrosis and surgical difficulty later.<br><br>Tuberculosis (option A), Candida (option B), Pseudomonas (option C), and Klebsiella (option E) are less common pathogens.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A 12-year-old child has a midline neck swelling that elevates on deglutition but not significantly on tongue protrusion. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Thyroglossal cyst","Dermoid cyst","Branchial cyst","Cystic hygroma","Thyroid swelling"],a:4,e:"Thyroid swellings move mainly with swallowing because of attachment to laryngeal framework. Tongue protrusion movement develops clinically minimally compared with thyroglossal cysts.<br><br>Careful examination helps distinguish thyroid lesions from congenital midline neck anomalies.<br><br>Thyroglossal cyst (option A), branchial cyst (option C), cystic hygroma (option D), and dermoid cyst (option B) behave differently.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The foramen cecum represents the embryological origin of the:",o:["Parathyroid gland","Branchial fistula","Thyroid diverticulum","Submandibular gland","Cystic hygroma"],a:2,e:"The thyroid gland begins embryologically as thyroid diverticulum arising from foramen cecum at tongue base. Persistent remnants develop clinically into thyroglossal anomalies.<br><br>The gland descends through neck connected temporarily by thyroglossal duct.<br><br>Parathyroid gland (option A), branchial fistula (option B), submandibular gland (option D), and cystic hygroma (option E) arise differently.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A child undergoing Sistrunk operation develops postoperative seroma. The most appropriate initial management is:",o:["Immediate re-exploration","Chemotherapy","Total thyroidectomy","Needle aspiration with pressure dressing","Radiotherapy"],a:3,e:"Small postoperative seromas are commonly managed conservatively after thyroglossal surgery. Mild neck swelling develops clinically without severe infection signs.<br><br>Aspiration and compression usually prevent further fluid reaccumulation effectively.<br><br>Immediate re-exploration (option A), chemotherapy (option B), thyroidectomy (option C), and radiotherapy (option E) are unnecessary.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with thyroglossal cyst carcinoma requires additional thyroidectomy mainly when:",o:["Cyst wall is thin","Histology confirms papillary carcinoma with thyroid involvement suspicion","Patient is younger than 10 years","Cyst is located below hyoid","Infection is present"],a:1,e:"Additional thyroidectomy may be required when associated thyroid malignancy is suspected clinically or radiologically. Cervical nodal metastasis develops clinically in advanced papillary carcinoma.<br><br>Management decisions depend on age, tumor extent, and thyroid gland findings.<br><br>Thin cyst wall (option A), young age (option C), subhyoid location (option D), and infection (option E) are insufficient indications.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A 14-year-old child with recurrent infected thyroglossal cyst is planned for definitive surgery. Which operative procedure provides the lowest recurrence rate?",o:["Simple cyst excision","Needle aspiration with antibiotics","Radical neck dissection","Sistrunk operation","Marsupialization only"],a:3,e:"Sistrunk operation is the gold-standard procedure for thyroglossal cyst management. Recurrent sinus formation develops clinically after incomplete excision procedures.<br><br>The surgery removes cyst, tract, and central hyoid bone because remnants frequently pass through this region.<br><br>Simple excision (option A), aspiration (option B), neck dissection (option C), and marsupialization (option E) have higher recurrence rates.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient undergoes surgery for infected thyroglossal cyst during active inflammation and later develops recurrence. The major reason for delaying definitive surgery until infection settles is:",o:["Prevention of thyroid storm","Reduction of salivary fistula","Prevention of facial nerve palsy","Avoidance of tracheostomy","Reduced risk of recurrence and tissue plane distortion"],a:4,e:"Operating during acute infection increases fibrosis and obscures normal anatomical planes. Persistent fistula and recurrence develop clinically after inadequate tract excision.<br><br>Initial antibiotics followed by delayed definitive surgery improves surgical clearance significantly.<br><br>Thyroid storm prevention (option A), facial palsy avoidance (option C), tracheostomy prevention (option D), and salivary fistula reduction (option B) are less relevant reasons.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A child develops persistent mucoid discharge from midline neck six months after thyroglossal cyst surgery. The most appropriate definitive management is:",o:["Repeated aspiration only","Oral corticosteroids","Revision Sistrunk procedure","Radiotherapy","Thyroid suppression therapy"],a:2,e:"Persistent postoperative thyroglossal fistula usually indicates residual epithelial tract remnants. Continuous discharge develops clinically through previous operative scar or sinus opening.<br><br>Revision Sistrunk procedure with complete tract excision provides definitive treatment.<br><br>Aspiration (option A), corticosteroids (option B), radiotherapy (option D), and thyroid suppression (option E) are ineffective definitive measures.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient undergoing Sistrunk operation develops postoperative dysphagia and neck swelling with respiratory discomfort. The most important immediate complication to exclude is:",o:["Seroma only","Wound hematoma","Hypocalcemia","Branchial fistula","Salivary adenitis"],a:1,e:"Postoperative hematoma is an important early neck surgery complication because expanding swelling may compromise airway rapidly. Respiratory distress develops clinically within hours after surgery.<br><br>Urgent wound assessment and decompression may become lifesaving interventions.<br><br>Seroma (option A), hypocalcemia (option C), branchial fistula (option D), and salivary adenitis (option E) are less acute emergencies.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A 30-year-old woman undergoes excision of thyroglossal cyst carcinoma. Histology confirms papillary carcinoma with suspicious thyroid nodules on ultrasound. The next preferred management step is:",o:["Observation only","Broad-spectrum antibiotics","Radical mastoidectomy","Completion thyroidectomy evaluation","Pure tone audiometry"],a:3,e:"Papillary carcinoma arising in thyroglossal remnants may coexist with thyroid gland malignancy. Cervical nodal metastasis develops clinically in advanced thyroid carcinoma.<br><br>Further thyroidectomy assessment becomes important when synchronous thyroid lesions are suspected radiologically.<br><br>Observation (option A), antibiotics (option B), mastoidectomy (option C), and audiometry (option E) are inappropriate next steps.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A 19-year-old patient presents with a painless fluctuant swelling along the upper anterior border of sternocleidomastoid muscle. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Thyroglossal cyst","Branchial cyst","Dermoid cyst","Cystic hygroma","Laryngocele"],a:1,e:"Branchial cyst classically presents as painless cystic swelling along anterior border of sternocleidomastoid muscle. Recurrent infection develops clinically after upper respiratory tract infections.<br><br>The lesion commonly arises from persistent second branchial cleft remnants.<br><br>Thyroglossal cyst (option A), dermoid cyst (option C), cystic hygroma (option D), and laryngocele (option E) show different anatomical locations.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A branchial fistula most commonly opens externally at the:",o:["Midline below hyoid bone","Suprasternal notch","Posterior triangle apex","Lower anterior border of sternocleidomastoid","Submental region"],a:3,e:"Branchial fistulas typically open near lower anterior border of sternocleidomastoid muscle. Persistent mucoid discharge develops clinically from the sinus opening.<br><br>The tract usually extends internally toward the tonsillar fossa.<br><br>Midline hyoid region (option A), suprasternal notch (option B), posterior triangle (option C), and submental region (option E) are uncommon sites.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A 35-year-old smoker presents with cystic lateral neck swelling. Which diagnosis must be excluded before labeling it as branchial cyst?",o:["Thyroglossal cyst","Lipoma","Metastatic squamous cell carcinoma","Dermoid cyst","Cystic hygroma"],a:2,e:"Cystic neck masses in adults may represent metastatic squamous carcinoma from occult head and neck primary. Dysphagia and cervical lymphadenopathy develop clinically in advanced disease.<br><br>Adult lateral neck cysts should therefore be considered malignant until proven otherwise.<br><br>Thyroglossal cyst (option A), lipoma (option B), dermoid cyst (option D), and cystic hygroma (option E) are less dangerous considerations.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest embryological origin of branchial cyst is persistence of:",o:["First branchial cleft","Thyroglossal duct","Third branchial pouch","Fourth branchial pouch","Second branchial cleft"],a:4,e:"Second branchial cleft anomalies are the commonest congenital lateral neck lesions. Painless upper neck swelling develops clinically in adolescents and young adults.<br><br>Failure of obliteration of cervical sinus contributes to cyst formation embryologically.<br><br>First cleft (option A), third pouch (option C), fourth pouch (option D), and thyroglossal duct (option B) are less frequent origins.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with branchial cyst develops acute tenderness, erythema, and fever. The initial management should include:",o:["Immediate radical excision","Chemotherapy","Broad-spectrum antibiotics","Total thyroidectomy","Radiotherapy"],a:2,e:"Acute branchial cyst infection should first be managed conservatively with antibiotics. Painful inflamed swelling develops clinically during secondary bacterial infection.<br><br>Definitive surgery is delayed until inflammation resolves to reduce operative difficulty and recurrence.<br><br>Immediate excision (option A), chemotherapy (option B), thyroidectomy (option D), and radiotherapy (option E) are inappropriate initial treatments.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"During surgical excision of a second branchial fistula, the tract classically passes between the:",o:["Common carotid artery and trachea","Lingual nerve and hypoglossal nerve","Facial artery and vein","Internal jugular vein and vagus nerve","External and internal carotid arteries"],a:4,e:"Second branchial fistula tracts typically course between external and internal carotid arteries toward tonsillar fossa. Persistent neck discharge develops clinically from congenital sinus openings.<br><br>Knowledge of this relation is essential to avoid vascular injury during surgery.<br><br>Carotid-tracheal plane (option A), facial vessels (option C), jugular-vagus relation (option D), and lingual-hypoglossal pathway (option B) are incorrect.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A branchial cyst aspirate classically contains:",o:["Bile pigments","Thyroid follicles","Keratinized cartilage","Cholesterol crystals","Hemosiderin only"],a:3,e:"FNAC from branchial cyst commonly demonstrates cholesterol crystals and keratinous debris. Painless lateral neck swelling develops clinically over years.<br><br>Aspiration findings help differentiate branchial cyst from metastatic lesions and abscesses.<br><br>Bile pigments (option A), thyroid follicles (option B), cartilage (option C), and isolated hemosiderin (option E) are less characteristic.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The definitive treatment for branchial cyst is:",o:["Repeated aspiration","Complete surgical excision","Oral steroids only","Incision and drainage alone","Radiation therapy"],a:1,e:"Complete surgical excision is the definitive management for branchial cysts and fistulas. Recurrent infection develops clinically if lesions remain untreated.<br><br>Careful dissection minimizes recurrence and neurovascular complications.<br><br>Repeated aspiration (option A), steroids (option C), incision alone (option D), and radiotherapy (option E) are inadequate treatments.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops weakness of lower lip after branchial cyst surgery. The most likely injured structure is:",o:["Lingual nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Vagus nerve","Marginal mandibular nerve"],a:4,e:"Marginal mandibular branch of facial nerve may be injured during upper neck surgery. Lower lip asymmetry develops clinically during smiling and speaking.<br><br>The nerve runs superficially near mandibular margin and remains surgically vulnerable.<br><br>Lingual nerve (option A), glossopharyngeal nerve (option C), vagus nerve (option D), and hypoglossal nerve (option B) produce different deficits.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A complete branchial fistula opens internally into the:",o:["Pyriform fossa","Vallecula","Nasopharynx","Tonsillar fossa","External auditory canal"],a:3,e:"Second branchial fistulas commonly terminate internally within tonsillar fossa. Mucoid neck discharge develops clinically through external opening.<br><br>Embryological persistence of branchial apparatus explains this characteristic tract pathway.<br><br>Pyriform fossa (option A), vallecula (option B), nasopharynx (option C), and auditory canal (option E) are less common sites.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A lateral congenital neck swelling that brilliantly transilluminates is more suggestive of:",o:["Branchial cyst","Dermoid cyst","Cystic hygroma","Lipoma","Sebaceous cyst"],a:2,e:"Cystic hygroma contains lymph-filled spaces producing brilliant transillumination clinically. Airway compromise develops clinically in extensive lesions of infancy.<br><br>Branchial cysts usually transilluminate poorly because of thicker cyst contents.<br><br>Branchial cyst (option A), dermoid cyst (option B), lipoma (option D), and sebaceous cyst (option E) do not transilluminate prominently.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with branchial fistula undergoes surgery. The most important reason for complete tract excision is to:",o:["Prevent thyroid dysfunction","Prevent recurrence","Improve hearing","Reduce salivation","Avoid airway edema only"],a:1,e:"Incomplete branchial tract excision leaves epithelial remnants behind, leading to recurrence. Persistent discharge develops clinically from residual sinus openings.<br><br>Complete removal of entire tract is therefore essential during definitive surgery.<br><br>Thyroid dysfunction (option A), hearing improvement (option C), salivation reduction (option D), and airway edema prevention (option E) are less relevant goals.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A first branchial cleft anomaly is closely associated surgically with the:",o:["Facial nerve","Recurrent laryngeal nerve","Lingual nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Accessory nerve"],a:0,e:"First branchial cleft anomalies often lie near parotid gland and facial nerve branches. Facial weakness develops clinically after accidental surgical injury.<br><br>Careful nerve identification is therefore crucial during excision procedures.<br><br>Recurrent laryngeal nerve (option B), lingual nerve (option C), hypoglossal nerve (option D), and accessory nerve (option E) are less closely related.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with infected branchial cyst develops fluctuation despite antibiotics. The next appropriate step is:",o:["Immediate thyroidectomy","Radical mastoidectomy","Radiation therapy","Observation only","Needle aspiration or drainage"],a:4,e:"Abscess formation within infected branchial cyst may require drainage in addition to antibiotics. Fever and painful swelling develop clinically in severe infections.<br><br>Definitive excision is planned after acute inflammation subsides.<br><br>Thyroidectomy (option A), radiation (option C), observation alone (option D), and mastoidectomy (option B) are inappropriate interventions.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A 22-year-old patient has recurrent watery discharge from congenital neck opening since childhood. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Thyroglossal cyst","Complete branchial fistula","Laryngocele","Sebaceous cyst","Lipoma"],a:1,e:"Complete branchial fistulas present with chronic intermittent mucous discharge from congenital external opening. Recurrent infection develops clinically in neglected lesions.<br><br>The tract often extends deeply toward tonsillar fossa internally.<br><br>Thyroglossal cyst (option A), laryngocele (option C), sebaceous cyst (option D), and lipoma (option E) usually do not discharge persistently.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The investigation most useful for delineating branchial fistula tract preoperatively is:",o:["Tympanometry","Pure tone audiometry","Bronchoscopy","Fistulography or CT scan","Sialography"],a:3,e:"Imaging studies such as fistulography or CT help define tract anatomy before surgery. Persistent neck discharge develops clinically in complete fistulas.<br><br>Accurate delineation reduces operative complications and incomplete excision risks.<br><br>Tympanometry (option A), audiometry (option B), bronchoscopy (option C), and sialography (option E) are unrelated investigations.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops recurrence after branchial cyst excision because the surgery was performed during active infection. The major operative problem in infected lesions is:",o:["Hyperthyroidism","Tissue plane distortion by fibrosis","Facial edema only","Hypocalcemia","Salivary obstruction"],a:1,e:"Inflammation and fibrosis obscure tissue planes during surgery for infected branchial lesions. Residual epithelial tissue develops clinically into recurrent cysts or fistulas.<br><br>Elective surgery after infection resolution improves surgical clearance significantly.<br><br>Hyperthyroidism (option A), facial edema (option C), hypocalcemia (option D), and salivary obstruction (option E) are less important concerns.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A cystic neck mass in an adult with associated weight loss and dysphagia should be considered malignant until proven otherwise because it may represent:",o:["Dermoid cyst","Thyroglossal cyst","Lipoma","Sebaceous cyst","Metastatic HPV-related oropharyngeal carcinoma"],a:4,e:"HPV-related oropharyngeal carcinoma commonly presents with cystic cervical nodal metastasis in adults. Dysphagia and occult tonsillar lesions develop clinically in many patients.<br><br>Misdiagnosis as benign branchial cyst delays definitive oncological treatment.<br><br>Dermoid cyst (option A), thyroglossal cyst (option B), sebaceous cyst (option D), and lipoma (option C) are less concerning possibilities.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops postoperative tongue weakness after excision of a deep branchial fistula tract. The most likely injured nerve is:",o:["Facial nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Recurrent laryngeal nerve","Phrenic nerve"],a:2,e:"Deep branchial fistula surgery may place hypoglossal nerve at risk because of close anatomical relationships. Tongue deviation develops clinically toward side of injury.<br><br>Careful superior neck dissection minimizes this complication.<br><br>Facial nerve (option A), glossopharyngeal nerve (option B), recurrent laryngeal nerve (option D), and phrenic nerve (option E) produce different deficits.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The best timing for definitive branchial cyst surgery is:",o:["During acute infection","Immediately after aspiration","During active abscess formation","Only after age 40 years","After complete resolution of inflammation"],a:4,e:"Elective surgery after inflammation subsides permits safer dissection and complete excision. Recurrent sinus formation develops clinically after inadequate surgery during acute infection.<br><br>Clear tissue planes reduce recurrence and neurovascular injury risk significantly.<br><br>Acute infection (option A), immediate aspiration period (option B), delayed age criteria (option D), and active abscess stage (option C) are inappropriate timings.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A newborn presents with a large soft cystic swelling in the posterior triangle causing respiratory distress. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Branchial cyst","Thyroglossal cyst","Cystic hygroma","Dermoid cyst","Laryngocele"],a:2,e:"Cystic hygroma is a congenital lymphatic malformation commonly presenting in posterior triangle of neck. Airway compromise develops clinically in large neonatal lesions.<br><br>The lesion consists of multiloculated lymph-filled cystic spaces that infiltrate surrounding tissue planes.<br><br>Branchial cyst (option A), thyroglossal cyst (option B), dermoid cyst (option D), and laryngocele (option E) present differently.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The embryological origin of cystic hygroma is abnormal development of the:",o:["Branchial arches","Thyroglossal tract","Salivary ducts","Parathyroid glands","Lymphatic system"],a:4,e:"Cystic hygroma results from sequestration of primitive lymphatic tissue failing to communicate normally. Massive neck swelling develops clinically during infancy or prenatal life.<br><br>The lesion often infiltrates neck spaces extensively and may extend into mediastinum.<br><br>Branchial arches (option A), thyroglossal tract (option B), parathyroid glands (option D), and salivary ducts (option C) are unrelated origins.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A neck swelling that brilliantly transilluminates in infancy is most suggestive of:",o:["Branchial cyst","Dermoid cyst","Sebaceous cyst","Lipoma","Cystic hygroma"],a:4,e:"Cystic hygroma contains clear lymphatic fluid producing brilliant transillumination clinically. Respiratory compromise develops clinically when lesions enlarge significantly.<br><br>This examination finding helps differentiate it from other congenital neck masses.<br><br>Branchial cyst (option A), dermoid cyst (option B), sebaceous cyst (option C), and lipoma (option D) usually transilluminate poorly.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A neonate with giant cystic hygroma develops severe airway obstruction immediately after birth. The immediate priority in management is:",o:["Radical excision","Chemotherapy","Airway stabilization","Radiotherapy","Thyroidectomy"],a:2,e:"Large cervical cystic hygromas may compress upper airway critically in neonates. Cyanosis and respiratory distress develop clinically within minutes after delivery.<br><br>Securing airway takes precedence before definitive surgery or sclerotherapy planning.<br><br>Radical excision (option A), chemotherapy (option B), radiotherapy (option D), and thyroidectomy (option E) are inappropriate emergency priorities.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"Cystic hygroma is most commonly located in the:",o:["Midline below hyoid bone","Retropharyngeal space","Submental region","Parotid region","Posterior triangle of neck"],a:4,e:"Most cystic hygromas arise within posterior triangle because of abnormal jugular lymph sac development. Progressive neck swelling develops clinically in infancy.<br><br>The lesion frequently extends across fascial boundaries into mediastinum or axilla.<br><br>Midline neck (option A), submental region (option C), parotid region (option D), and retropharyngeal space (option B) are less common sites.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with extensive unresectable cystic hygroma is planned for non-surgical treatment. The preferred modern option is:",o:["Radioiodine ablation","Chemotherapy alone","Radical neck dissection","Total thyroidectomy","Intralesional sclerotherapy"],a:4,e:"Large infiltrative hygromas may not be safely excisable because of proximity to vital structures. Persistent swelling develops clinically despite partial surgery.<br><br>Sclerotherapy using agents like bleomycin or OK-432 effectively reduces lesion size.<br><br>Radioiodine (option A), neck dissection (option C), thyroidectomy (option D), and chemotherapy (option B) are inappropriate therapies.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"Cystic hygroma is strongly associated with which chromosomal disorder?",o:["Down syndrome only","Turner syndrome","Klinefelter syndrome","Marfan syndrome","Fragile X syndrome"],a:1,e:"Cystic hygroma demonstrates significant association with Turner syndrome and other chromosomal abnormalities. Prenatal neck swelling develops clinically during fetal ultrasonography.<br><br>Abnormal lymphatic drainage contributes to characteristic lesion formation embryologically.<br><br>Down syndrome (option A), Klinefelter syndrome (option C), Marfan syndrome (option D), and Fragile X syndrome (option E) are less strongly linked.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"During surgical excision of cystic hygroma, the major operative difficulty is due to:",o:["Excessive calcification","High vascularity only","Associated thyroid enlargement","Rapid malignant transformation","Infiltration into surrounding tissue planes"],a:4,e:"Cystic hygromas frequently infiltrate deeply between neurovascular structures and fascial compartments. Recurrence develops clinically after incomplete excision.<br><br>This infiltrative nature makes complete surgical clearance technically challenging.<br><br>Calcification (option A), isolated vascularity (option B), malignant transformation (option D), and thyroid enlargement (option C) are less important difficulties.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A postoperative complication most likely after cystic hygroma excision involving posterior triangle is injury to the:",o:["Facial nerve","Recurrent laryngeal nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Lingual nerve","Accessory nerve"],a:4,e:"The spinal accessory nerve traverses posterior triangle and may be injured during extensive neck surgery. Shoulder drooping develops clinically after trapezius paralysis.<br><br>Careful nerve preservation is therefore essential during cystic hygroma excision.<br><br>Facial nerve (option A), recurrent laryngeal nerve (option B), lingual nerve (option D), and hypoglossal nerve (option C) are less exposed.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A child develops recurrence after partial excision of cystic hygroma. The main reason for recurrence is:",o:["Thyroid dysfunction","Salivary obstruction","Residual lymphatic malformation tissue","Malignant degeneration","Branchial pouch persistence"],a:2,e:"Incomplete excision leaves microscopic lymphatic channels behind within surrounding tissues. Progressive swelling develops clinically because residual lesions continue enlarging.<br><br>Recurrence is therefore common after subtotal excision procedures.<br><br>Thyroid dysfunction (option A), salivary obstruction (option B), malignant degeneration (option D), and branchial pouch persistence (option E) are unrelated mechanisms.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A 32-year-old smoker presents with a painless cystic swelling at the upper jugular region. FNAC reveals squamous cells with keratin debris. Before diagnosing branchial cyst, the surgeon must primarily exclude:",o:["Dermoid cyst","Thyroglossal cyst","Metastatic oropharyngeal carcinoma","Lipoma","Cystic hygroma"],a:2,e:"Cystic cervical metastasis from HPV-related oropharyngeal carcinoma may mimic branchial cyst in adults. Dysphagia and occult tonsillar lesions develop clinically in many cases.<br><br>Careful endoscopic examination and imaging are mandatory before labeling adult lateral cystic lesions as congenital.<br><br>Dermoid cyst (option A), thyroglossal cyst (option B), lipoma (option D), and cystic hygroma (option E) are less dangerous possibilities.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with thyroglossal cyst develops sudden painful enlargement with fever and erythema. The best initial management is:",o:["Immediate Sistrunk operation","Radiotherapy","Radical neck dissection","Hemithyroidectomy","Broad-spectrum antibiotics"],a:4,e:"Secondary infection commonly complicates thyroglossal cysts in children. Painful tender swelling develops clinically during acute inflammatory episodes.<br><br>Definitive surgery should be delayed until infection subsides to reduce recurrence and operative complications.<br><br>Immediate surgery (option A), neck dissection (option C), thyroid surgery (option D), and radiotherapy (option B) are inappropriate first-line measures.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A 4-year-old child presents with midline neck swelling that elevates on tongue protrusion. Which operative step is essential to minimize recurrence?",o:["Removal of sternocleidomastoid muscle","Removal of thyroid gland","Tracheostomy","Radical lymph node dissection","Removal of central hyoid bone"],a:4,e:"The thyroglossal tract commonly passes through or near the central hyoid region. Persistent fistula develops clinically after incomplete excision procedures.<br><br>Sistrunk operation includes hyoid removal specifically to reduce recurrence rates significantly.<br><br>Sternocleidomastoid removal (option A), thyroidectomy (option B), lymph node dissection (option D), and tracheostomy (option C) are unnecessary.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient undergoing excision of second branchial fistula develops postoperative tongue deviation toward operated side. The injured structure is the:",o:["Facial nerve","Accessory nerve","Lingual nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Vagus nerve"],a:3,e:"The hypoglossal nerve lies close to deeper portions of branchial fistula tracts. Tongue deviation develops clinically toward side of injury because of ipsilateral muscle paralysis.<br><br>Careful superior neck dissection helps prevent this surgical complication.<br><br>Facial nerve (option A), accessory nerve (option B), lingual nerve (option C), and vagus nerve (option E) produce different deficits.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A newborn with giant cystic hygroma extending into mediastinum is planned for treatment. Which investigation best defines extent of lesion preoperatively?",o:["Tympanometry","CT or MRI neck and mediastinum","Audiometry","Bronchoscopy only","Thyroid scan"],a:1,e:"Cross-sectional imaging accurately demonstrates deep extension and relation to neurovascular structures. Airway compression develops clinically in extensive cervicomediastinal lesions.<br><br>Preoperative mapping is essential for surgical planning or sclerotherapy decisions.<br><br>Tympanometry (option A), audiometry (option C), bronchoscopy alone (option D), and thyroid scan (option E) are inadequate assessments.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops recurrence after branchial cyst surgery performed during active infection. The major reason for recurrence is:",o:["Hyperthyroidism","Vocal cord paralysis","Salivary obstruction","Thyroid storm","Tissue fibrosis obscuring surgical planes"],a:4,e:"Inflammation and fibrosis distort normal anatomy during surgery for infected congenital neck lesions. Residual epithelial remnants develop clinically into recurrent cysts or fistulas.<br><br>Elective surgery after resolution of infection improves complete tract excision significantly.<br><br>Hyperthyroidism (option A), salivary obstruction (option C), thyroid storm (option D), and vocal cord paralysis (option B) are less relevant issues.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with thyroglossal cyst carcinoma is found to have suspicious thyroid nodules on ultrasound. The next appropriate management consideration is:",o:["Observation only","Radical mastoidectomy","Sialography","Pure tone audiometry","Completion thyroidectomy evaluation"],a:4,e:"Papillary carcinoma arising in thyroglossal remnants may coexist with thyroid gland malignancy. Cervical lymph node metastasis develops clinically in advanced thyroid carcinoma.<br><br>Further thyroid surgery is considered when associated thyroid involvement is suspected.<br><br>Observation (option A), mastoidectomy (option B), audiometry (option D), and sialography (option C) are inappropriate next steps.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with posterior triangle cystic hygroma develops shoulder drooping after surgery. The most likely injured nerve is:",o:["Hypoglossal nerve","Facial nerve","Lingual nerve","Accessory nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve"],a:3,e:"The spinal accessory nerve traverses posterior triangle and remains vulnerable during extensive cervical surgery. Shoulder weakness develops clinically because of trapezius paralysis.<br><br>Meticulous nerve preservation is important during cystic hygroma excision procedures.<br><br>Hypoglossal nerve (option A), facial nerve (option B), lingual nerve (option C), and glossopharyngeal nerve (option E) are less exposed.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A 25-year-old patient presents with persistent mucous discharge from congenital opening near lower anterior sternocleidomastoid border. The definitive treatment is:",o:["Repeated aspiration","Broad-spectrum antibiotics lifelong","Complete surgical excision of fistulous tract","Radiotherapy","Observation only"],a:2,e:"Branchial fistulas require complete tract excision for definitive cure. Persistent discharge and recurrent infection develop clinically if residual epithelial tissue remains.<br><br>Careful tract dissection minimizes recurrence and neurovascular injury risks.<br><br>Repeated aspiration (option A), lifelong antibiotics (option B), radiotherapy (option D), and observation (option E) are inadequate strategies.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A child develops postoperative airway compromise hours after Sistrunk operation for thyroglossal cyst. The most likely immediate surgical complication is:",o:["Seroma","Wound hematoma","Salivary fistula","Hypocalcemia","Branchial recurrence"],a:1,e:"Postoperative neck hematoma is a dangerous complication because expanding swelling may rapidly compromise airway. Respiratory distress develops clinically within early postoperative period.<br><br>Urgent wound decompression and airway assessment may become lifesaving interventions.<br><br>Seroma (option A), salivary fistula (option C), hypocalcemia (option D), and branchial recurrence (option E) are less acute emergencies.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
];